{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473336"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2352"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2352"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.07,0.03,0.46,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81299"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2352"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66641"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1322"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81299"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nine-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a tonic-clonic seizure. He was sitting at the table having breakfast when he started convulsing. The seizure stopped in the ambulance and he now appears confused. He was born at term and his developmental milestones were delayed. He has struggled academically. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. He was adopted and his family history is unknown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. He has axillary freckling and several caf\u00e9-au-lait macules larger than 5 mm in diameter on his chest.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be present on ophthalmological examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Angiofibromas","Cataract","Glaucoma","Lisch nodules","Vestibular schwannoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1), including seizures, learning difficulties, axillary freckling, and caf\u00e9-au-lait macules. NF1 is an autosomal dominant neurocutaneous syndrome caused by mutations in the NF1 gene on chromosome 17.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELisch nodules\u003C/strong\u003E are pigmented iris hamartomas that are the most common ophthalmological finding in NF1. They appear as dome-shaped, elevated lesions on the iris and are present in over 90% of adults with NF1. Their presence, along with other clinical features, helps confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngiofibromas\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of tuberous sclerosis, another neurocutaneous syndrome that presents with ash-leaf spots and shagreen patches rather than the caf\u00e9-au-lait macules seen in NF1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECataracts\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibular schwannomas\u003C/strong\u003E are hallmark features of neurofibromatosis type 2 (NF2), which typically presents in late adolescence or early adulthood. NF2 is a distinct condition from NF1 and is caused by mutations in a different gene.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with Sturge-Weber syndrome, which presents with port-wine stains and leptomeningeal angiomas rather than the cutaneous findings seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of multiple diagnostic criteria for NF1 (caf\u00e9-au-lait macules, axillary freckling, neurodevelopmental issues) should prompt comprehensive evaluation including ophthalmological examination and brain MRI to assess for optic nerve gliomas, which occur in about 15% of children with NF1.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) is characterised by caf\u00e9-au-lait macules, axillary freckling, neurofibromas, and Lisch nodules.","Seizures and learning difficulties are common neurological manifestations of NF1.","All patients with NF1 should undergo MRI brain and orbits to screen for optic nerve gliomas."],"references":["Ly KI, Blakeley JO. The Diagnosis and Management of Neurofibromatosis Type 1. Med Clin North Am. 2019; 103:1035-54. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31582003/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66641"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2352"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66641"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T19:44:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T19:44:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2352"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81299"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagno